.Dd March 28, 2026
.Dt CHKFLAGS 1
.Os Xao
.Sh NAME
.Nm chkflags
.Nd check BSD file flags
.Sh SYNOPSIS
.Nm
.Op Fl v
.Op Ar file ...
.Sh DESCRIPTION
The
.Nm
utility displays the system and user-level file flags associated with the specified
.Ar file
operands. These flags, such as immutability or append-only status, are specific to the 
underlying filesystem and provide protections beyond standard POSIX permissions.
.Pp
If no
.Ar file
is specified,
.Nm
operates on the current directory.
.Pp
The following options are supported:
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It Fl v
Verbose mode. Displays the numerical bitmask alongside the human-readable labels.
.El
.Sh ENVIRONMENT
.Bl -tag -width "POSIXLY_WRONG"
.It Ev POSIXLY_WRONG
If set,
.Nm
may display extended attributes or internal kernel-only flags that are normally 
hidden for compatibility.
.El
.Sh EXIT STATUS
.Ex -std
.Sh EXAMPLES
Check flags for a sensitive system file:
.Pp
.Dl $ chkflags /bin/sh
.Pp
Check flags for all files in the current directory:
.Pp
.Dl $ chkflags *
.Sh SEE ALSO
.Xr chflags 2 ,
.Xr ls 1 ,
.Xr stat 2
